Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 diamonds in the dataset with 81 features . Most variables are numeric in nature. Some of the categorical variables are Loan status, occupation and employment status.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

when we hear about loans we tend to think majorly borrowing and lending.The general objective of this project is to study the determinants that contribute to loan borrowing and payment. Some of the questions I want to answer using this dataset are:

  • What factors influences a loans outcome?
    • Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?
    • Is the prosper risk management efficient
    • Does the prosper score and rate impact on borrowers rate

The main features of interest will therefore be loanstatus, loan original amount and monthly loan payment. Any other variable that play a role in loan borrowing and lending will also be investigated

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help with the investigation are: loanstatus, borrowerAPR, borrowerRate, listing category, prosperrating, monthly income, occupation, term and employment status.

In [17]:
THRESHOLD = 2000
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
occupation_frequency = loans['Occupation'].value_counts()
idx = np.sum(occupation_frequency > THRESHOLD)
most_occupation = occupation_frequency.index[:idx]
loans_sub = loans.loc[loans['Occupation'].isin(most_occupation)]
freq = loans_sub['Occupation'].value_counts()

occ_freq = freq.index
sb.countplot(data=loans_sub, x='Occupation', color= base_color, order=occ_freq     );
plt.xticks(rotation=80);

Excluding the occupation 'other'we have borrowers who are professionals being the most common occupation.

Q8. What are the common Loanstatus among borrowers.

What other insights can we draw from the categorical variables "Term" and "IsBorrowerHomeowner"?

In [21]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=2, figsize = [15,15])

sb.countplot(data = loans, x = 'Term', color = base_color, ax = ax[0,0])

sb.countplot(data = loans, x = 'IsBorrowerHomeowner', color = base_color, ax = ax[0,1])

sb.countplot(data = loans, y = 'EmploymentStatus', order=loans.EmploymentStatus.value_counts().index, color = base_color, ax = ax[1,0])

sb.countplot(data = loans, y = 'LoanStatus', order=loans.LoanStatus.value_counts().index, color = base_color, ax = ax[1,1])

plt.tight_layout()

Most loans have a term of three years(36 months), followed by 5 years(60 months) then 1 year. There are more loan borrowers who are homeowners as compared to those who are not. Most loan borrowers are employed. Most people who are retired and not employed borrow less as compared to those who are not.

'LoanStatus' and 'EmploymentStatus' are nominal categorical data thus the order of the display of the bars can be computed with the following logic:

  • Count the frequency of each unique value in the columns, and sort it in descending order
  • Plot the bar chart in the decreasing order of the frequency of the 'Loanstatus'

We can see that the LoanStatus('current') has the most number of counts. Few borrowers have passed due and almost pay in time and there is about 3000 defaulted

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the borrowers pay in time and there is about 3000 defaulted Loan and a little percentage that passed their due date.

Most loans have a term of three years(36 months), followed by 5 years(60 months) then 1 year.

Most borrowers take a Loan for Debt Consolidation

Most loan borrowers are in full time employment

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distribution of the MonthlyLoanPayment had a long right tail. I performed a log transformation and the new plot had a big spike between 150 to 200 dollar.

The distribution of monthlyiIncome is highly skewed to the right.To uncover a reason why I perforemed summary stattistics and noticed a very huge range between the maximum value and the third quartile value. My new plot contained only values below a certain threshold. Most of the monthly income for the borrowers is in range 2k to 6k.

def boxplots(x, y, **kwargs):
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color, order=loans_1.LoanStatus.value_counts().index)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = loans_1, y_vars = numeric_vars, x_vars = 'LoanStatus',
                size = 3, aspect = 5)
g.map(boxplots)

Conclusions¶

The major questions I wanted to answer with this data set are given below together with the findings

  • What factors affect a loans outcome status?

Defaulted and completed loans is not very much dependent on proper rating.

Borrowers who have completed their loan payment often borrow for 3 years and their credit score fall in most in A and D.

There is a negative correlation between monthly income and loan status in past due the lower the income, the more will be the delay in payment.

There is a slight positive correlation between loan status and loan original amount in that: borrowers that pass their due date ask for a higher loan amount as compared to those who completed.

Borrowers who default have less loan original amount.

  • Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

Most borrowers who need a loan of high amount make it for 5 Years

Some borrowers ask for multiples of 5 or fractions of 5.

There is an approximately positive linear ralation between Monthly loan payment and Loan original amount. High monthly loan payments are made for loans that are high.

  • Is the prosper risk management efficient?

Defaulted and completed loans is not very much dependent on proper rating.

  • Does the prosper score and rate impact on borrowers rate?

Borrowers with better prosper score and rating are charged less interest for loans.

  • Other relevant findings

In general homeowners get a lower interest rate across the years as compared to those who are not homeowners.

The top 3 occupations in terms of monthly loan payment are judge, doctor and pharmacist. The groups that have lower monthly loan payment are students.

Most of the monthly income for the borrowers is in range 2k to 6k.

Most loans have a term of three years(36 months), followed by 5 years(60 months) then 1 year.

Most borrowers take a Loan for Debt Consolidation

Most loan borrowers are in full time employment

Most monthly loan payments made are between 150 to 200
